👀 How do you show up for yourself?⁠
⁠
😍 2022 has been my year to show up for me. I've been battling to find strategies to stop my frequent migraines, shuttling back and forth to treatments and prioritizing my health and fitness. I've been focusing on building community in my new home, facing my fears and deep-seated anxieties, and trying to adult in a way that makes me feel happy and settled. ⁠
⁠
😛 And after a year of showing up to share about small businesses, brand partners I believe in, and destinations I've loved, I'm also showing up for my business.⁠
⁠
👉🏽 For the next week I’m doing the cringey thing, I’m showing up to promote my subscription community. I'll be telling you all about it, why I love it, what you get as a member, and why it's so important to my work. ⁠
⁠
❓️Cause if I don't show up for myself who will?⁠
⁠
🙏🏽 If you rock with me and my work, first and foremost THANK YOU. I know we all hate to be sold to, but please stick with me over the next week. Don't just tune out! Your engagement and support through this campaign (be it by subscribing or just sticking around to hear about the community and check out the content) is so important! ⁠
⁠
🥳 I've set a wild goal to cross 3k paid subscribers by the end of this campaign. It's ambitious but I'm hopeful! THINK WE CAN DO IT?⁠

💜 Imagining myself as the main character 

I’ve had some fascinating conversations with friends in the last 24 hours about ai, representation, privacy, and so much more. 

These conversations build on and echo some of what I learned this past week in DC while I was attending a program focused on influencers, disinformation, and democracy… namely that technology is an amazing tool but can also replicate and amplify our worst traits (like how we can code our own biases into the algorithms and programs we build).

For now, issues aside, I do love that programs like the one I used to generate these images (Lensa ai app) allow folks who typically don’t see themselves represented to become the main character.

Some of these made me immediately want to dye half my hair white and get an asymmetrical cut with some fab jewelry. They feel fantastical and otherworldly in a sense.

But also in many of the photos generated I’m thinner and lighter skinned, which I’m sure speaks to what the ai predicts we’ll find pleasing *deep sigh*

👉🏽 We're going car-free! ⁠
⁠
😅 We are getting rid of our car in favor of public transit and bike commuting.
⁠
😬 Yes, bike commuting scares the absolute sh*t out of me, but one of my long-term goals remains to get comfortable jetting around on my bike. And luckily Portland has decent bike infrastructure and Ahmed will hold my hand along the way. So if you pass some curly-haired person screaming to herself as cars get close just keep it moving and ignore me.⁠
⁠
💚 Ultimately, with this move and all the transition of the last few years, we want to refocus on our big priorities. And for the foreseeable future, that means paying off debt and making money moves. ⁠
⁠
☕️ And no matter what the finance pages say, cutting dinners and lattes isn't going to get us there. Saving on big-ticket items that we don't need (like a CAR) will help a lot more than skipping coffee. That's also why I've been pushing hard to break 100k followers on IG and expand onto TikTok. Cause yeah I think the numbers are largely bs but at the same time, a bigger more diversified platform is a step toward increasing my income. So this is my season of cutting costs and raising rates. ⁠
⁠
🤑 Capitalism sucks and it does wild, harmful things to all of us. But to me at least, money is a useful tool. After a few months of Ahmed not having a job (he did get a job recently YAY) and us not having health insurance, ooh does money seem like a tool for stability and freedom. The kind of freedom Ahmed and I definitely want for ourselves. ⁠

👀 What are your travel dreams for 2023?⁠
⁠
🙏🏽 I'm so thankful for the travel opportunities I had this year. The chance to explore more of my own home, to visit places that have old memories for me and that are completely new, to travel and try out some of the dopest Black food you can find anywhere... I couldn't have imagined that this would be my life. ⁠
⁠
😊 I'm daydreaming about next year as I look through these pics from some of my fave travel moments in 2022 and trying to envision what I want my life and work to look like. ⁠
⁠
✈️ Travel is definitely a part of that dream, though slower travel and less frequent travel are top of my list. I daydream about time to dig in when I'm traveling rather than hopping around every few days. ⁠
⁠
🎄 I also want to have time to really explore Portland and travel in the PNW. I want to learn my way around, to really feel at home, to find the best spots in the region for staycations which we absolutely need as we adapt to multigenerational living. ⁠I wanna find all the Black and BIPOC-owned gems in general and connect with the local folks doing dope work right here at home.⁠
⁠
👋🏼 Beyond that, I daydream about learning more about myself through travel. Yes, I'm a Black American woman, but I'm also the granddaughter of a Japanese artist who spent much of her life in Switzerland. I have family ties to California. I made a life with my husband in Jordan and so much of the woman I am today was shaped in a short but intense summer in Oman. My childhood memories involve a red tricycle and my uncle and auntie in Vermont. People and places have shaped who I am and I hope to be able to explore that in the coming year through travel. ⁠
⁠
👉🏼What are your 2023 daydreams, travel-related and beyond?⁠

⬇️ All the spicy noods!⁠
⁠
📍Stretch The Noodle, food cart at the SW 3rd and Washington pod downtown  in Portland, OR⁠
⁠
Things To Know: There was a little line when we went but it moved quickly. The menu is simple, with a few noodle dishes to choose from and a special or two based on the day. There are options to get tofu or vegetables with your order. ⁠
⁠
What We Liked: I got the Dan Dan Noodles (has pork) that I LOVED. Just the right blend of spicy and savory for me. Ahmed got the Chao Man, a noodle stir fry with vegetables where you can pick your protein. He devoured his. The dumpling special was definitely the star though. Those dumplings were so stuffed and so juicy! ⁠
⁠
Cost: We spent $42 with tip for two noodle entrees and an appetizer. The portions are LARGE and both of us ended up having leftovers. ⁠

🖤 Hey boo hey, I'm Anela Malik ⁠
⁠
There are so many new faces here! I wanted to say THANK YOU for choosing to let me share a bit of my journey with you! ⁠
⁠
8 THINGS TO KNOW ABOUT ME:⁠
⁠
😎 I have two cats, Percy and Sukkar, that we adopted when we lived in Amman, Jordan, and brought back to the US with us. ⁠
⁠
🏘️ I recently moved to Portland, Oregon, but for work and just because I'm a wanderer in general I tend to bounce all over. So you might see me pop up in your city soon.⁠
⁠
🖋️ I like to write and am in the final stages of finishing my book (shoutout to Nat Geo for believing in ya girl). My brain feels pretty wrung out but once this project is done I can't wait for that moment in a few months when the fog clears and the inspo  strikes me again.⁠
⁠
📕 I'm a speed reader and can read a book in a day. I was the kid who used to get a long fantasy epic novel and crush it in an afternoon. ⁠
⁠
🛫 Travel is one of my lifelong loves and I've gone from the student ultra-budget traveler to someone who now leans towards luxury travel and outdoor adventures.⁠
⁠
🌽 Trying a new restaurant is one of my greatest joys. I LOVE to cook but something about the experience of a restaurant brings me so much joy.⁠ I make a point to share about Black-owned restaurants (and businesses in general) wherever I find them. You'll also see a mix of whatever else I've got going on here on my page.⁠
⁠
🤗 I curse a lot. I tone it way down here but if you ever meet me irl you've been warned.⁠
⁠
🥸 I don't tolerate any fuckery here. Don't be mean because you're upset about your own life. This isn't the space for hate, fatphobia, or any other issues better worked out with yourself.⁠
⁠
WELCOME to my little corner of the internet. Thanks for being here. ⁠
⁠
👏🏽 NOW TELL ME 👉🏽 what should I know about you?⁠

“As travel bloggers, should we have more conversations about the impacts of overtourism?” ⁠
⁠
Shoutout to @diywithjoy_ for asking this on Twitter⁠! ⁠
⁠
👉🏾 My answer is of f*cking course we should be, as long as those conversations are true to our beliefs & interests. Let’s get into it. ⁠
⁠
Overtourism is when “too many tourists travel to a popular destination, causing the place to suffer negative environmental, economic, and sociocultural impacts." (dictionary.com⁠)⁠
⁠
❓️But what does that MEAN? ⁠
⁠
“When rent prices push out local tenants to make way for vacation rentals, that is overtourism. When narrow roads become jammed with tourist vehicles, that is overtourism. When wildlife is scared away, when tourists cannot view landmarks because of the crowds, when fragile environments become degraded – these are all signs of overtourism." (responsiblevacation.com)⁠
⁠
Visiting my family in Hawaii recently, I thought about this a lot. Tourism to HI has been hotly debated in recent years. And especially when we visited my fam in popular West Maui, between looking for parking & paying $55 for a burrito + a tostada I couldn't really relax even though Maui is incredible. ⁠
⁠
And we leave once our holiday ends. For people like my fam who live in HI tourism seems to be a double-edged sword. So many jobs are in the service industry & rely on tourism. Yet the volume of visitors puts a strain on infrastructure, housing, & more.⁠
⁠
Travel creators have to wrestle with their own approach to this, weighing when & what to share + which partnerships make sense. ⁠
⁠
🤷🏾‍♀️ All of this is why on my trip I shared via stories & a glimpse here & there, but didn't make content in the ways I typically do. I don't have an answer that feels right yet. And this is just one personal trip. Capitalism & travel being part of my job adds a whole other layer.⁠

Sometimes your joy triggers others and when they lash out it's extremely painful, but it's not really about you. ⁠
⁠
That's a lesson I have to keep learning over and over again living my life very out loud and online. ⁠
⁠
In my case, or in our case, Ahmed seems to be the trigger for many. Almost every single week for two years I've gotten a comment or DM along the lines of "but you married a white man so you're full of sh*t when you share about all this Black-owned stuff." These comments are always from other Black folks.⁠
⁠
And I WANT to react. I can't help it. I want to explain. ⁠
⁠
Explain that race and identity are complicated and my husband's name is Ahmed in a post 9/11 America. That if we tried to make connections across communities we might just find that more people than we think struggle with the impacts of white supremacy.⁠
⁠
Explain that I also love white men. The way I do asian men and Black men and well, just men. Because I can't believe we are all born equal regardless of race or ethnicity and then guard my heart against anyone who doesn't fit the idea of the perfect Black man that I may never meet at the right time. ⁠
⁠
Explain that I've had the space to share about Black-owned businesses and Black stories for years on my platform, even when it doesn't pay or the fever of June 2020 has died down, largely because of Ahmed. Because of his support, his willingness to drive as far as we need to to try this spot I heard about, to help provide us the financial stability and a safe space for me to chase this online dream of mine. ⁠
⁠
Explain that to me, there is nothing finer than someone who shows up for you, who works to grow together with you, who knows they can't walk in your shoes but chooses empathy anyway. ⁠
⁠
But it's not about me. It's not about us. And no one should have to explain who or how they love as consenting adults. ⁠
⁠
It's about them.⁠
⁠
So to them I'll just say, I hope you find love in your life like this. The kind that shows you how much more you can be and how much more life can offer than you ever imagined. ⁠
⁠
And also feel free to fuck all the way off.⁠

Savannah 🖤 + Solo Travel Tips ⬇️⁠
⁠
I LOVED the week I recently spent in Savannah, GA! It was such a good solo adventure and even though I was working I felt so relaxed. ⁠
⁠
I have tons of Savannah recs coming, but I also wanted to share some solo travel tips! ⁠
⁠
I get so many questions from folks who have never traveled alone before but are intrigued (and also scared) by the idea. Here's my best advice if that's you: ⁠
⁠
1️⃣ - Go somewhere you've been before! Especially if this is your first trip alone and you're nervous, go somewhere you're familiar with! I've been to Savannah before with friends and that definitely made it easier for me to get around, plan out what I wanted to do, and feel confident doing it solo this trip. ⁠
⁠
2️⃣ - Pick a smaller destination. I'd suggest picking a city or area mid-sized or smaller (population 500kish or less) for your first solo travel adventure as it'll just be easier to learn your way around. Even for me as a very experienced traveler, I recognize how much more labor and effort I will have to put into navigating and planning activities in a large metro area like NYC or LA than I will have to in a smaller place like Savannah. Unless you're a big city babe at heart and used to the hustle and bustle of large, crowded, fast-moving cities, then I say go for it!⁠
⁠
3️⃣ - Send someone your itinerary in advance! Even for travel to places I know and feel very comfortable in, like Savannah, I try to stay in the habit of sending my husband my itinerary, hotel info, etc. No one likes to think about the worst-case scenario, but even if things go mildly off track it's always good to have someone know where you are and when to start missing you. ⁠
⁠
And even though travel content can romanticize solo travel to the extreme, it's not for everyone. It might be your thing, it might not be and that's okay.⁠
⁠

⬇️ This @washingtonianmag piece 🙄⁠
⁠
Not because it's entirely inaccurate, but because it is the same exact piece I've been reading about influencers for ten years. ⁠
⁠
🙄 The formula goes like this: A few salacious incidents of influencer bad behavior sure to get people riled up + a few notes about the positive impacts of influencers + condescending and judgemental language that makes it seem like influencers are devoid of any true skill + a clickbaity headline. ⁠
⁠
🥱 How boring. You'd think with the institutional backing of a magazine we'd be getting better articles by now. Or at least asking different questions.⁠
⁠
👿 Generally, I do think that influencers not disclosing free shit makes it easy for people to take shots at the industry. From DC to Portland and beyond I see so many free meals, comped hotel stays, press trips, and more without a single note or # of disclosure. It's easy for people to paint us all as vapid and greedy when folks continue to do this. ⁠
⁠
🥸 BUT, that's a conversation that I'd love to have with a bit of nuance. We should ask similar questions about traditional media orgs, their policies on comped experiences, and ask ourselves if this is an influencer thing or a capitalism thing. Cause I've been on many trips with journalists getting flown out for free in exchange for coverage.⁠
⁠
☠️ We've gotten to a stage where some creators are running independent media businesses that can compete with and far surpass the reach of legacy media. So why are we still writing articles about how they don't need to have any skill? How they just need to be shameless? ⁠
⁠
❓️Where are the questions about how they craft their internal policies? How they decide what not to cover? What their stance is on free shit? What the challenges of working in a largely unregulated industry are like? How they view diversity in the industry?⁠
⁠
Why are we not writing about influencers like they're just people with jobs? Jobs that, I might add, are VERY SIMILAR to many legacy media jobs.⁠ ⁠
⁠

⬇️ Things you should know about visiting Jordan Part 1️⃣! ⁠
⁠
❤️ I love Jordan, I lived there for 2.5 years, & have visited many times. I'm 100% sure that after seeing more of my recent trip you'll be adding Jordan to your  list, so here's tips for your trip planning: ⁠
⁠
👉🏽 US citizens can get a visa on arrival for 40 Jordanian Dinars (about $56 USD) at most ports of entry, EXCEPT the King Hussein Bridge. ⁠At Queen Alia Airport you can pay with cash or card on arrival and the visa on arrival line is clearly marked. ⁠Also check into a Jordan Pass if you’re visiting Petra to save $$.
⁠
👉🏽 While many places in Jordan do take cards, plan to have some cash on hand as you will need it in some places. One Jordanian Dinar is worth about $1.40 USD. I typically use ATMs to get cash when I’m in Jordan or you can change money at money exchange places. ⁠
⁠
👉🏽 While in the capital city of Amman, you can easily get around via taxi or Uber. Outside of the capital, you can get around by hiring a driver, booking a tour, or renting a car. Though the driving may be a bit more aggressive than you're used to, depending on where you're from, I'd say confident drivers would do fine here. I did when I lived here. ⁠
⁠
👉🏽 Summer here can get HOT, so look to spring and fall (March to May and Sept to Nov) for your Jordan travel plans to try to beat the heat. Also, be sure to research when Ramadan is happening so that you can plan around it. Many things are closed or will have altered schedules during Ramadan.⁠
⁠
Jordan has so much to offer, such welcoming people, great food, and incredible history... I highly recommend visiting! ⁠
⁠

🖤 HAVING MANY HOMES⁠
⁠
Home to me is more concept than place. I have many "homes." ⁠
⁠
Home is forever where my mom lives. No matter where she moves to or what changes in her life, I know how my mom's house will smell, what it will feel like when I walk in. It's forever home.⁠
⁠
DC still feels like home. I go back often enough and still have my favorite places, my people there. It still feels safe and familiar when I step off the plane there. It has that energy. ⁠
⁠
Home is also where all of my stuff is in Portland, Oregon, and really wherever Ahmed and our cats are. Though of any of the places that I consider home, I have the most trouble with Portland. I'll be honest I've struggled immensely since moving here, and continue to struggle here. So far Portland is not a space where I feel particularly at ease or confident. It's a space where I often feel isolated and frankly sad, which makes it hard to find much inspiration there. ⁠
⁠
Jordan is definitely still home in my heart, one I'm so thankful I got to revisit during a hard Portland winter. I need many more weeks there just to sit, drink tea and catch up, to feel a bit like myself again.⁠
⁠
I'm leaning into the escape and opportunity that travel offers and hope to explore much more of home and my own history this year, places like @experienceoman and @experienceegypt where I learned just what I was capable of as a young traveler and made connections that I treasure to this day.⁠
⁠
I hope to also explore @visitjapan.us, where I have so much family, so many family stories, where my granny's long-delayed burial will finally be, but are new to me. And maybe even @visitcalifornia, where places like @crockerart, @lacma, @moca and more have my grandpa's art. I'd like to explore how his story and his art somehow leads to my today. ⁠
⁠
I'm hoping that in the process I can remind myself of who I am, and maybe even build up some of the cracks in myself so that even in Portland I can feel a bit more at ease. ⁠

Revisiting Jerash 🇯🇴⁠
⁠
Jerash is home to some of the best-preserved Greco-Roman ruins in the world. The site is only about an hour's drive away from Jordan's capital city of Amman and offers incredible views. In the springtime, you'll often find the hills where the ruins sit full of wildflowers. I love spending a half-day walking around and exploring. ⁠
⁠
Jerash also holds a lot of memories for me. It's a place where I took every friend or family member who visited when we lived in Jordan. It's also where my mom and I once saw Andrea Bocelli perform, sitting right there in the ancient city listening to his voice as the night fell. That memory reminds me that life can hold much more than I imagined, if I'm open to it. ⁠

⬇️ Things that have helped me process during this transition that's full of grief but also wonder and excitement...⁠
⁠
It's a work in progress and I'm taking it day by day, but here's what has helped me feel more like me:⁠
⁠
💥 Journaling, sometimes multiple times a day whenever a mood strikes. ⁠
⁠
💥 Therapy, though I've slowed down on therapy as intensive therapy got expensive very very fast.⁠
⁠
💥 Moving my body. Those silly little hot girl walks always lift my spirits even when I don't wanna do it. ⁠
⁠
💥 Prioritizing my own pleasure. Some days that might mean reading steamy books for hours, others it might be going for ice cream with friends. But doing things that make me feel good are non-negotiable right now. ⁠
⁠
💥 Long phone calls with friends and family. My community helps me feel like me again and reminds me when I'm down that I'm that bitch and are right there with me to celebrate my progress.⁠
⁠
💥 Travel. Travel has reminded me how insignificant my problems are in the grand scheme of things and has reminded me how kind people generally are. Plus, my concept of home has had to evolve as I start over, so it's nice to spend some extended time outside of home right now to take a break. ⁠
⁠
💥 Letting myself feel the feelings. Yes, this means sitting with it when I feel like shit. Crying, writing about it, and just acknowledging that yes, this is how I feel. ⁠
⁠
💥 Affirmations. I have a note on my phone that I read out loud every morning of affirmations and reminders for myself. I tell myself that nobody gets to be mean to me, not even me. ⁠
⁠
⁠
Cheers to muddling on through the very messy parts. ⁠

This is the first time in my adult life that I only have to worry about myself.⁠
⁠
First, I had to juggle school and work, often working multiple jobs and going to class, just trying to keep it all together until I finished grad school. Then it was a career, partner, pets, and this little experiment on the internet. At some point I was somehow in training in the Foreign Service, still working as a server at a restaurant in DC, plus navigating living with someone who was finishing grad and also needed support. I spent years and years doing the absolute most.⁠
⁠
I don't glorify that hustle. I did those things because I had goals, because I had to to make it work, and because I wanted to be a good partner.⁠
⁠
But now, for the first time at 32, I just have myself to manage. No other person's schedule to navigate, no pets though I miss my kitties every day, no second job, no classes... ⁠
⁠
And don't get me wrong, I still feel like I'm juggling a lot. Being an entrepreneur is not for the faint of heart. Running a business while trying to finish writing a book demands a sort of mental flexibility that consistently frustrates me. But even on my longest days now, I feel free in a way I haven't before.⁠
⁠
I'm realizing that I carried far too fucking much for too long, for myself and for other people. And maybe it's selfish, but the life I want moving forward, whether I continue working for myself, get another job, stay single, move to a new place, or end up with someone again, no matter what shape it takes, I'm not doing that anymore. ⁠

⬇️ Tips For Dining Alone: ⁠
⁠
If you’re nervous about dining solo, this is for you. ⁠
⁠
1. You are entitled to have fun and experience new things alone! Try to get out of your head if possible. No one is staring at you and no one is bothered by you being alone. People are generally focused on themselves and if you do feel like they’re staring at you just tell yourself it’s because you’re fucking fly as hell living your best life.⁠
⁠
2. Bring something to do. Unless you like staring off into space, I suggest bringing a book, your kindle, a journal, or a podcast and headphones so you have something to keep you entertained during those quiet down moments of the meal. ⁠
⁠
3. Ask questions. Some restaurants don’t put reservations for one on their online booking pages. And some places will only do tasting menus for 2 or more people. When in doubt, call or dm to see if you can get clarity. ⁠
⁠
4. It’s okay to ask for a table solo. Many restaurants will seat solo diners at the bar. And while I do love the bar because I can watch the bartender work and often chat with people, I’m also so short that my legs dangle and it’s uncomfortable for me because I usually can’t reach the footrest on the bar stool. I’ll ask, politely, if I can have a table rather than the bar, and usually places are fine with it as long as I’m ordering food and not just drinks. ⁠
⁠

🧐 Why don’t I move back to DC? ⁠
⁠
I get this question all the time, so let’s talk about it! ⁠
⁠
DC still feels like home to me. I love the museums, that there's so much going on, the food scene is so dynamic, there's music and shows to catch, my friends are here, there's public transit. ⁠
⁠
But I left DC because the cost of living just didn't make the life or work I wanted feel possible. And unfortunately, that hasn't changed. ⁠
⁠
I'm a freelancer with unpredictable income. Health insurance is expensive y'all. By living where I live now, my cost of housing is HALF of what I would pay in DC. Other things are also more affordable. The money I save makes it possible to visit DC when I want to (every 3 months typically) and I've been able to slow down, take days off, take better care of myself, and even save for a rainy day while not feeling like I have to hustle all the time.⁠
⁠
DC is also an expensive place to run my business. I want Feed The Malik to support the small businesses you see on my platform by paying for my meals and services when I go in. Generally, my partnerships are with bigger national brands, and then if you see me out showcasing a local business, I pay for that.⁠
⁠
There are some exceptions of course. Sometimes places recognize me and send out free stuff. Sometimes if it's a bigger ticket item like a hotel stay I'll work for a discount or a free room. You'll always see that disclosed when I do. But the kind of DC sharing I used to do when I lived here costs thousands and thousands of dollars.⁠
⁠
For me living in DC again is a dream that just doesn't make sense right now. Maybe one day. Maybe if my subscription community grew enough that I could take a month off of brand deals and still pay my salary and business expenses. That, or some similar situation would be the time. When I could live here and really LIVE, work, rest, and nurture myself the way I imagine and also feel secure.

"How do I get comfortable riding my bike around?"⁠
⁠
I get this question a LOT and I get it. You may see me now riding around town on my cute af new bike from @livcycling (who I've worked with and bought bikes from on my own before FYI), looking carefree, but I had actual panic attacks when I first started riding as my brain was trying to convince me that I was not going to survive this. ⁠
⁠
Here's what helped me along the way:⁠
⁠
1. Start where you are and go at your own pace. I started by riding around my neighborhood on roads and paths I already knew well, going just a few blocks at a time. I asked friends and family to come with me on these first short rides, even just to the store down the block. Starting small in a familiar place helped a lot! ⁠
⁠
2. Look for welcoming bike spaces! Check with local bike shops and bike orgs and ask about social/beginner-friendly group rides. That way you can start riding in new places with other people and get to know folks who are also figuring out this biking thing. ⁠Also, accounts like @allbodiesonbikes and @realjennarose are so welcoming and provide so much inspo and resources.⁠
⁠
3. If cars make you nervous, there's no shame in walking or driving until you get to a place that feels safer for you. I will still get off and walk on the sidewalk through a busy intersection and when I first started, I did that a LOT. I also like riding on urban trails that are completely separate from the road, so I will put my bike in the car and drive to parking at the trail, then take my bike out and ride there where I feel safer. If this is part of your hesitation, look for bike trails and paths near where you live. ⁠
⁠
4. Ignore other people's advice if it doesn't work for you. I am forever being told I need clip-in pedals for efficiency. But my goal isn't efficiency, it's to have fun and feel the sun on my face. And I had an experience in the past with clip-in pedals that made me so scared I didn't ride a bike for a year after. Always take safety info seriously, but beyond that, ride your own ride.⁠
⁠
Fellow cyclists, what other advice do you have for folks?⁠

🥰 How the heck did I get here?⁠
⁠
A few years ago I was messing around on the internet trying to learn skills for what I thought would be a long-term career doing public diplomacy work in the Foreign Service. ⁠
⁠
I knew learning how to write for public consumption, edit photos and videos, speak on camera and in public settings, and all those other things content creators do could be useful for the work I wanted to do as a diplomat, so I went for it.⁠
⁠
I never expected this hobby to grow so fast or offer me opportunities and freedoms I couldn't have in the Foreign Service. I never thought this could be my job and that I would actually leave that old life behind. ⁠
⁠
I did, and that's how Feed The Malik was started. I didn't really have a plan but I wanted a change and figured why not?⁠
⁠
That question has taken me to wild places in my life.⁠
⁠
It's how I ended up studying and working and traveling in the Middle East, learning Arabic and then getting a master's degree in Arab Studies from Georgetown. I was having fun, so why not continue?⁠
⁠
It's how I ended up living in NW Arkansas not once but twice, because I felt like I needed peace and nature and a strong sense of community, so why not go looking for it?⁠
⁠
That's also a big part of how I decide what to share here. Because I want to show folks, especially Black women, that living out loud can be so joyful and freeing, despite other people's judgment. Why not be ourselves as long as we're not hurting others?⁠
⁠
This space is really a product of my curiosity and desire to keep learning and I'm so thankful it's grown to be so kind, so nurturing, so curious, and so fun. Working for myself has been the hardest thing I've ever done and the hours have often been LONG, but I also do think I have the coolest job in the world. I get to go out and ask myself, why not?⁠
⁠
Anyway, that's a very roundabout intro. What else do you wanna know about me or Feed The Malik? Drop it in the comments and I'll reply individually to your questions.⁠

⬇️ My superpower is that I will Google anything⁠
⁠
I say a lot that you won’t have the life you want if you don’t go looking for it. I truly believe that applies to everything from the way we treat our bodies to the information we encounter. ⁠
⁠
I think social media has made us feel like what we want will be served to us by the algorithm, without having to go looking. Maybe sometimes that’s true. But social media will have us missing out, as evidenced by the questions I get every week.⁠
⁠
“How do you find Black-owned businesses?”⁠
⁠
“Is there a Black food festival in Georgia?”⁠
⁠
“How did you make friends in your new home?”⁠
⁠
I’m happy to answer as much as I can (sometimes I just can’t get through my all comments and DMs tbh). But beyond trying to save my poor thumbs, I really want to encourage folks to go out and look for what they want. You will not find it if you don’t go looking for it! ⁠
⁠
There is so much information available online and search engines will even pull social media posts that answer your questions, so you can get the best of all resources if you get on your search game.⁠
⁠
That’s why I consider being willing to Google anything one of my superpowers.⁠
⁠
I have lived in some white af places and immediately found diverse community because I searched for events, newsletters, and local orgs that aligned with what I wanted. And yes, I then had to leave my house and put myself out there to make those connections but I used Google to point me in the right direction. ⁠
⁠
I find most of the businesses I highlight on my page by searching things like “Black-owned restaurants in X city” and just going from there. ⁠
⁠
When I was a student I landed two fellowships that changed my life, that offered MORE THAN $100K of benefits, travel, etc, that I found on Google. No one at my school had ever told me about them, I’d never heard of them before...⁠
⁠
This is not to say stop asking me questions! Just consider it a gentle call in bc I simply can’t answer every question thrown my way. BUT my content always has enough info for you to find more on your own <3⁠

My bff and I have said to each other many times in recent years that we miss our old selves. The young, and yes sometimes dumb, but also bold, fearless, wild selves who didn't fear failure as much, didn't fear rejection as much. Who leapt. ⁠
⁠
And for the past six months, I now realize that's the core of what I've been working on. Reclaiming parts of my old self. ⁠
⁠
The wild little Anela would apply for shit she wasn't qualified for, go halfway across the world where she knew no one to stay for a while, walk up to a man and tell him he's fine and that he should buy her a drink, tattoo her asscheeks because it felt like fun decoration, and do weird dances in public.⁠
⁠
Now I definitely hesitate more, I'm more cautious and frankly less dumb, but I've slowly started to feel like parts of that girl are more present in me again. That maybe I can integrate the two, can live boldly and be straight delulu (as my friend and forever inspiration @lissettecalv says) while also honoring the lessons I've learned through grief and trauma.⁠
⁠
So that's what I'm working on. I'm trying to intentionally reclaim parts of my old self and it's wild and scary and fun.⁠
⁠
And tbh I couldn't do it without my people, my core group of friends who truly know me and see me and can remind me sometimes of who the fuck I am when I forget. ⁠Love y'all. ⁠

⬇️ How hard is to get around if you don’t speak the language?⁠
⁠
I’d say Japan is a relatively easy destination to navigate if you speak English and don’t speak Japanese. ⁠
⁠
Locals are generally helpful and patient. I found when interacting with folks at hotels, restaurants, on public transit, etc, that people were patient with me, didn’t seem frustrated that I was speaking English plus whatever hand gestures I could think of, and were very willing to try to make it work so we could understand each other. ⁠
⁠
Yes, in major cities especially lots of folks speak English. In addition, generally, public transit has English-language signage and announcements. Even when I was outside of bigger cities I found that to be the case. ⁠
⁠
I always say try to learn a few phrases to be polite, be willing to wade into communicating using whatever tools you have at hand (gestures, facial expressions, google translate) and you can make it work! ⁠
⁠
Pro tip: you can use @google translate’s photo feature to translate menus at restaurants! Also, many restaurants, though not all, have photos on the menu, so you can also use that to help guide you when ordering. ⁠
-—⁠

⁠

⁠
For flights: I have a longstanding subscription to @hello_going and have seen Japan flight deals pop up there! You can also set up fare alerts on @google Flights or other services to see when there are price drops on fares. ⁠

Generally, I’ve found traveling within your budget is very possible in almost every destination. I do always say though, the more money you want to save the more time you’ll spend researching in advance. That’s the trade off! ⁠

⁠
But honestly, we always said we would, and very rarely did we actually make it happen. Even though we both know how precious our time together is, life got in the way. We were busy. The burden of planning was too much on top of everything else. For all the reasons, it didn't happen like it should have. ⁠
⁠
And this hike/bike/kayak trip we got to go on with @intrepidtravel was everything. Yes, it was gifted and ya girl was working. But more than that, we got to show up each day and just hang out together, knowing that we would both be able to see and do and eat and try dope stuff without having to do hours and hours of research to figure out which bus to take when and what rental spot was best where. ⁠
⁠
Joining a group trip removed that planning burden and gave us space to just enjoy trying something new together. Even though the itinerary we picked was tough as it was super active, we left already talking about doing something like it again next year. We left thinking yeah, next year we can really do this. We can pick a destination, pick a group trip with a travel company we trust, have that set price in advance so we know what to save for, and really make this happen together. ⁠
⁠
I can't wait. And shoutout to @intrepidtravel for hosting us, we had the most epic time.⁠
